You can also express this using a lateral join, which can be convenient particularly when there are multiple dependencies:

    select * 
    from test cross join lateral
         (values (extract(year from age(birthdate)))
         ) v(age) 
    where v.age &gt;= 24;

postgres doesn&#39;t allow column aliases in the where clause, if you need it in the where clause just use a copy of the column expression.


    select extract(year from age(birthdate)) as age from test
    where extract(year from age(birthdate)) &gt;= 24;

Here is a more elegant solution.  No extra functions and give you both the result you want and will execute faster.

    Declare  @test table (
      id INT,
      name VARCHAR(255),
      birthdate DATE
    );
    
    INSERT INTO @test (id, name, birthdate) VALUES (1, &#39;jhon&#39;, &#39;1975-12-12&#39;);
    INSERT INTO @test (id, name, birthdate) VALUES (2, &#39;doe&#39;, &#39;1994-09-22&#39;);
    INSERT INTO @test (id, name, birthdate) VALUES (3, &#39;billy&#39;, &#39;1994-09-25&#39;);
    INSERT INTO @test (id, name, birthdate) VALUES (3, &#39;bob&#39;, &#39;1995-09-30&#39;);
    
    /* For age accounting for leap years and no extra functions */

    select name,birthdate
    ,  year(getdate())-year(birthdate)
     - case when dateadd(yyyy,year(getdate())-year(birthdate),birthdate) &gt; getdate() then 1 else 0 end as Age
    from @test
    where year(getdate())-year(birthdate)
     - case when dateadd(yyyy,year(getdate())-year(birthdate),birthdate) &gt; getdate() then 1 else 0 end &gt;=24
    go

    /* Same data but using an inline table. */
    
    Declare  @test table (
      id INT,
      name VARCHAR(255),
      birthdate DATE
    );
    
    INSERT INTO @test (id, name, birthdate) VALUES (1, &#39;jhon&#39;, &#39;1975-12-12&#39;);
    INSERT INTO @test (id, name, birthdate) VALUES (2, &#39;doe&#39;, &#39;1994-09-22&#39;);
    INSERT INTO @test (id, name, birthdate) VALUES (3, &#39;billy&#39;, &#39;1994-09-25&#39;);
    INSERT INTO @test (id, name, birthdate) VALUES (3, &#39;bob&#39;, &#39;1995-09-30&#39;);
    
    /* For age accounting for leap years and no extra functions */
    select *
    from (
        select name,birthdate
        ,  year(getdate())-year(birthdate)
         - case when dateadd(yyyy,year(getdate())-year(birthdate),birthdate) &gt; getdate() then 1 else 0 end as Age
        from @test
    ) d
    where d.Age&gt;=24

