You can actually combine `Readonly`, `Pick` and `Omit` to get the desired effect:

```ts
type ReadonlyByKey&lt;T extends {} , K extends keyof T&gt; = Readonly&lt;Pick&lt;T, K&gt;&gt; &amp; Omit&lt;T, K&gt;
```
[Play](https://www.typescriptlang.org/play/#code/C4TwDgpgBAShCGATA9gOwDYgEIgNIRAB4AVKCAD2AlUQGcoBvAXygBopczLq6oBrAsgBmUYgD4oAXlgIUGIgAUAlgGM+JdrjESAZFADyAWyXANHMQFgAUNdCQoASSmNrUN1HgAuKLWAAnJVQAcwBuV3cAI29fAODrJmtbcGgYZwdEQjgkNEwcfCIHdgByCKLtJPt0kglpZig9BigAbQUoQP5BEWIAXW9iFu6WIA)

The first intersection constituent picks the readonly members, while the second one picks the other members

**Edit**

A version to remove by type would be:
```ts
type KeyOfType&lt;T, V&gt; = {
    [P in keyof T]: T[P] extends V ? P: never
}[keyof T]

type ReadonlyByKey&lt;T extends {} , K extends keyof T&gt; = Readonly&lt;Pick&lt;T, K&gt;&gt; &amp; Omit&lt;T, K&gt;
type ReadonlyByType&lt;T, V&gt; = ReadonlyByKey&lt;T, KeyOfType&lt;T, V&gt;&gt;
``` 
[Play](https://www.typescriptlang.org/play/#)

This is a solution I came up with to do this based on a given type rather than a set of keys:

I&#39;m sure this can be simplified.

```ts
type KeysOfType&lt;T, O&gt; = {
  [P in keyof O]: O[P] extends T ? P : never;
};

type Values&lt;T&gt; = T extends { [k: string]: infer V } ? V : never;

type State = {
  message: string;
  counter: number;
};

type ReadonlyIfType&lt;T, O&gt; = Readonly&lt;
  Omit&lt;O, Exclude&lt;keyof O, Values&lt;KeysOfType&lt;T, O&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;
